# Styling: Reuse Existing Tokens Only

## Core Rules

1. **Always reuse existing defined variables and tokens.** Look up the project's SCSS variables, CSS custom properties, and design tokens before writing any style value.
2. **No hard-coded values.** Never use raw color hex/rgb, pixel sizes, font stacks, shadows, border-radii, spacing, or z-index values directly. Always reference an existing variable or token.
3. **No new variables or tokens.** Do not introduce new SCSS variables, CSS custom properties, or design tokens.
4. **No modifications to existing variables.** Never change the value or name of an existing variable or token definition.
5. **When no matching variable exists**, stop and ask the user what to do. Suggest best-practice options such as:
   - Reusing the closest existing token with a brief explanation of the trade-off
   - Deferring the change until the design system is updated
   - Flagging it as a gap for the design team

## Examples

```scss
// BAD — hard-coded color
.header { background: #3B82F6; }

// GOOD — reuses existing variable
.header { background: var(--primary-color); }
```

```scss
// BAD — hard-coded spacing
.card { padding: 16px; margin-bottom: 24px; }

// GOOD — reuses existing spacing token
.card { padding: $spacing-4; margin-bottom: $spacing-6; }
```

```scss
// BAD — adding a new variable
$my-new-blue: #1E40AF;

// GOOD — reuse what already exists or ask the user
```
